title: They have Their Issues, but Seem to be Cost Effective
text:
I'm 9 Months into using these Reusable K-Cups and have had varying experiences along the way:

For reference, I have a Kuerig 2.0

I'm the only one who uses these at home, and I use the in pairs: two 6 oz shots, which I read was recommended and can confirm is better than 12 oz through one.

The first two worked well in general.
On one (I'll refer to it as K-Cup #1), the lid broke pretty early: it was still usable, just less convenient.
The mesh started splitting on K-Cup #2 first, but it ended up lasting about as long as #1 (by which I mean that it leaked very few grinds for a long time).
K-cup #3 replaced #2, and my Kuerig didn't want to recognize it immediately: it took several attempts each time to get it to pass.
I experimented with #3, trying to find a pattern: I would spin it to see if orientation mattered and closed the lit with varying speeds and force. Eventually I slammed it hard enough that a chip busted out of the rim surrounding where the needle goes: since then the K-Cup has worked perfectly.
The Kuerig also would not recognize K-Cup #4: I tried my previous method of slamming it at first, thinking that I'd prefer the needle clear what space it needed (and that I'm seriously getting fed up with Kuerigs at this point and am thinking of switching back to traditional brewing methods), but couldn't get the needle to chip this cup. So, I took a knife and carved out some of the plastic rim; the K-cup now works about 75% of the time, which is obviously less often than #3 but is acceptable.

The other thing I have noticed is that the splitting is probably due to packing the K-Cup: at first I was stuffing grinds in there and forcing the lid closed; now I just pour the grinds in and brush the top so that the lid closes easily. This seems to improve the life span of the K-Cups somewhat.

Also, it can be used to make both shots and drip coffee. The only downside is that to get coffee that is the same quality as the standard illy capsules, you must tamp the coffee grounds correctly and there's a bit of a learning curve to that. If not packed tightly enough, the coffee will taste watered down; if packed too tight, you'll get less volume and it may taste a bit burnt. It's not difficult to do correctly, it just requires a little practice. Once you learn that technique, you can get espresso with perfect crema and full-bodied Italian cafe quality drip coffee. If you like to do multiple shots at a time, you'd be better off just using the standard disposable capsules (illy does have a great recycling program). title: Buy only if you love ironing. The end-of-cycle signal sounds like a child's ...
text:
Buy only if you love ironing. The end-of-cycle signal sounds like a child's toy and is so feeble, even on its loudest setting, that you can't hear it unless you're in the same room and there is no other noise. Furthermore, when the cycle is done, the dryer just stops, rather than continuing to tumble so that the clothes won't wrinkle. There is "wrinkle care" option that is supposed to keep the drum tumbling for a little while when the cycle is over, but it only turns the drum a quarter-turn once every minute, not enough to stop the wrinkles from setting in. Even worse, the "wrinkle-care" setting inexplicably disables the end-of-cycle signal completely. If you don't want to iron, you basically need to pull up a chair next to the dryer and sit there the whole time.

The dryer also has a special cycle to take the wrinkles out of a dry garment using steam. It shoots steam into the drum alright, but also plenty of liquid water along with it. So when the cycle is over, your shirt will be wrinkle-free but will have one sopping wet sleeve, for example.

It's pretty clear that LG doesn't have a clue about how laundry appliances are actually used. Avoid this brand.

text:
I needed a 30 inch free standing gas range.
What I wanted was 4 burners (not 5), and an oven.
That's it. No bells or whistles. Nothing extra. Just a simple design that was VERY WELL MADE..ACCURATE & PRECISE.
I looked at all the high end names, and read all the reviews. The icon seemed to be the best product for the money.
There were not allot of reviews for this particular item, and of the small number of reviews, some raved and some were dissatisfied. I was a bit stressed from the not so good reviews, but went ahead and bought this range.
I am a person who loves to cook, and bake.Â  I was hoping for precision, controlling the burners, and an oven that was consistent.
I am happy to report that this stove delivered.
I was prepared to have the gas air controls adjusted, (which would not be uncommon), but did not need to have anything adjusted.
The combination of the size and power of the burners works well for me, and they all have the ability to be adjusted precisely.
The oven is accurate and holds consistently.
After reading so many opinions, I have to admit that I don't understand how people go to some discount store, and grab an appliance because the price is low, (especially an appliance of this caliber),Â  and then expect miracles from it when there is no responsible customer-store relationship; no one who cares if the appliance was placed on the truck, and delivered with care, and respect; no one to call locally for help with any questions or problems that they may have.
I purchased my stove from a reputable family appliance store._(for as good a price as I had seen anywhere), Although I was happy with it right from the start, the store encouraged me to call with any questions, and assured me that if I needed any adjustments, they would promptly send an experienced service person.
This is a really nice unit for someone who enjoys cooking and appreciates simplicity._(I do not miss any of the useless electronics)
When the oven is holding at 450 degrees, the stove top, and controls remain cool to the touch. This tells me that the oven is well insulated. The weight of the stove and solid feel of the controls tells me that the stove was put together with care and integrity.
There is a learning curve with every new item.Â  No two stoves or ovens will work exactly the same. Just go with it. That is how you become proficient.
Yes I would recommend this stove to those who demand and appreciate the value of a well made tool.
SIX MONTHS LATER:
I am amazed at how pleased I am.
I look forward to using it everyday.
I love it's simplicity.. Not even a clock or timer. Just a great stove.

text: [[VIDEOID:d6498621e19ec53178ed5c11cf066c45]] Really pleased with this small countertop icemaker. Did a lot of research before buying--my small apt fridge doesn't make ice. This machine was recommended by Amazon and got good reviews. It came very well packaged and after I let it sit for 24 hours for the coolant to settle, it ran well from the first use. I use it approx once a week to make/bag enough ice for my morning iced latte. Obviously, it can make much much more. ð As promised, the machine makes a small batch about every 6-8 minutes. It doesn't keep the ice frozen once made but I've found I can wait til it makes at least 2-3 batches to scoop the cubes with minimal melting. I only use spring water in the machine. The ice cubes taste great. I've never noticed any off taste or odor. The only quirk I have noticed with the machine is if I let it sit for a few weeks without using it, when I use it again, it makes a wearing noise the first few times it takes up water but that goes away and it it runs pretty quietly. You can hear the fan running (like the low hum of a refrigerator) but it's easy to tune out and isn't loud enough to interrupt conversation or wake a baby. You can also hear the water running inside the machine. But again, not annoyingly loud. The machine wipes clean easily once you manually remove the stopper on the bottom right and let any remaining water drain out. (I catch the remaining water and use it on my plants.) I leave the machine's  top open and let it air dry after wiping out to prevent any moisture being trapped inside and growing mold. Once dry, I close the lid to keep out any dust or debris. The machine tells you when it needs more water and the buttons are easy to use. I like that I can turn it off when I'm done. Make sure to give it several inches of room around the fan and vent to maximize energy efficiency and extend the life of the unit. It comes with a basket that sets inside and a cute little white scoop.  Super happy with this purchase and definitely recommend this machine if a countertop icemaker option is best for you. I also love knowing exactly what is in the ice I'm consuming.

title: 4 stars
text: I really wanted a washing machine instead of going to the public laundry, and risking my clothes getting stolen or the machines eating my money. I bought this with high hopes. Overall, I am happy with it. It is durable. The wash cycle is adjustable up to 15 minutes, and the spin cycle is adjustable up to 5 minutes.  There are a couple of problems, however, which is why I removed a star. The inlet tube is small in width, made of thin plastic, and does not hook to any spout, rendering it basically useless because you have to hold it to the faucet the entire time while you basically get a trickle of water. I pour water in the washer with pitchers instead. The second problem is that you have to put the unit where there is a drain that is at the level of the washer or under it because the valve that drains the unit of water is at the bottom of the machine and short so you can't put the unit on the floor, and drain it into the bathtub or sink using the tube. The tube is too short for that. You basically have to put the unit in the bathtub or on a wide counter in the kitchen next to the sink to drain it into the sink unless you have a drain in your bathroom floor. [If you do, I am jealous :)] The final problem is that the spin container is significantly smaller than the wash container, so, if you wash a full load, you have to spin the clothes in shifts. As it is, you are already moving your load of clothes four times: 1) loading the washer with clothes; 2) loading the clothes into the spinner; 3) loading the clothes into the washer again to rinse them; 4) loading the clothes into the spinner a final tune to spin the excess water out. Add spinning the clothes in shifts, and you are talking about a lot of work. With that said, my clothes came out really clean, including the whites, and very dry. Please understand that this unit is not a dryer. It is a spinner to spin out excess water. That's it. You have to line dry your clothes after using it or use a machine dryer. I bought a mini dryer as well. Despite the problems, I am keeping it. Almost anything is better than going to the laundromat.

title: We went back to what works. A top loader that uses plenty of water and an agitator!
text: Top loading HE washers that actually work are a myth. After dealing with several it became obvious that filling a top loading drum 1/4 full with water then without an agitator try to get clothes clean was simply against the laws of physics. Yes front loaders can do it because they are able to tumble the clothes through the water but it's just not possible for a top loader to do the job with so little water and no agitator. We started looking at old school top loaders again since our laundry room just isn't configured to handle a front loader without some major remodeling plus we didn't like the idea of having to dry the inside of the door and gasket and leave the door cracked open to breath on the front loaders. We did a ton of research and reading and stumbled upon Speed Queen. The model AWN432 is an old school top loader that actually fills the drum with water and has an agitator. All the glowing reviews and stated years of trouble free service sold us. We went to our local appliance store and bought one on the spot. After we made the purchase the salesman said that was the 4th one he had sold in a week and that more and more people were looking for alternatives to HE top loaders. So far the Speed Queen has been rock solid with a total regular wash cycle of around 30 minutes compared to the hour or so the HE machines take. This machine handles odds loads like bath mats and mixed towels without any out-of-balance issues. In fact, I dare say you could set a glass of water on top, filled to the rim, and not a drop would slosh out. The clothes seem to be just as dry at the end of the cycle as they were in our HE washer so it does a good job of spinning out the water. It is so nice to not have to run multiple cycles and double rinse all the time to get our clothes just acceptably clean. So far we have yet to use the 2nd rinse feature on the Speed Queen. The Speed Queens have great warranties and are made with commercial duty parts (no plastic gears or bushings in these machines). The high capacity claims of the HE top loaders are just that- claims. If you want to have clothes that are clean from an HE you have to put in a lot less than the stated capacity. The Speed Queen can be stuffed full and still does a great job. So far we are totally satisfied with our new Speed Queen that is built like a tank. If anything changes I will update this review.

text:
Please Do Not trim away foam to fit as others have suggested, this is incorrect and will lead to problems. Push from fridge side with a purpose and assist retaining clips through from freezer side, it is tricky and you do have to push and rock diffuser to get clips to latch on freezer side. This is intentional so that it seals 100%. Item fit and function is perfect and it is OEM part. Great seller easy fix for stuck diffuser (usually burned out from icing by diffuser door caused by............poor sealing between fridge and freezer!

A lot of reviewers talk about a warm fridge from the diffuser sticking closed but it can also stick open (or get jammed open by ice) in that case it will lower your fridge temps to 30 or less. Sometimes just removing the diffuser and thawing it out will fix the problem.

Update: 2023-Still working. I will repeat what I originally said - Do Not Trim to Fit!- All reviewers who claim the attaching prong arms are not long enough are wrong, it is an illusion because the foam is shrunk on the original. Foam has open cell structure that will 'Give' when you install it. Push on the refrigerator side and assist locking tabs by reaching into the freezer side - it's very simple but does take some strength. If you are a woman or a girly man find a Man to assist you.

text: I needed this for a Kenmore double oven gas stove. The proper item (with screw tab that mounts the igniter on its edge) was $112 and up. This one worked fine with a minor modification. I had to carefully bend the screw tab downward in order to mount it on its edge. The other tab had to be cut off; which I did with a Dremel tool using a diamond cutoff wheel. Took all of about 5 minutes. I removed the plug from the old igniter and using the included ceramic wire nuts, attached the plug to the new igniter.  Another reviewer stated his wire nut did not want to lock on to the wires and apparently fell off, shorting and knocking out his control board. I experienced similar but remedied the problem by nipping (shortening) the bare wires. He apparently had his wire a bit too long and it bottomed out in the wire nut before it could grip and lock on. After nipping off about 1/16th in. the nut tightened properly and securely. The oven now works just fine. Note* As others have stated, just because your igniter glows does not mean it is good....it may not be getting hot enough to activate the temperature sensor to turn on the gas.

text:
3 or 4 month update: I'm still very happy with this hood and it sucks up nearly all heat, smoke, and steam, especially when using the back burners. Cooking smells lingering upstairs have definitely been reduced compared to the microwave. I am taking the rating down to 4 stars because I believe the lowest setting should be even lower while keeping high where it is. 75% of the time I use it on low, 20% on max, and 5% on 3. IF low were even lower then I could utilize the speed control more.

Original Review:

I just installed this hood a few days ago so the rating is based on my initial impressions. I am coming from a OTR microwave with a very loud and ineffective hood function even though it was ducted to outside. The Typhoon is much quieter on its lowest setting and probably more effective than the microwave was on high at the lowest setting. My duct work probably limits the highest settings on this hood but it seems to capture most steam and smoke. The controls work well enough but it would be nice if the light didn't turn off when the vents were turned off. The lighting itself is awesome.

Installation was not hard if you have moderate handyman skills. If you are a novice at handyman work then you'll do some cussing, especially if you were alone like I was. The biggest tip I have (stolen from other zephyr hood reviews) are to throw out the screws that came with the hood and get some hex head lag screws instead. This will make it much easier to tighten them after the hood is in place. The second tip is to make yourself a cardboard template of the hole location. To do this flip the hood upside down without any duct adapters on and trace out the hood along with the holes. Tape that to the installation location and you can drill right through the template. Finally I had to modify the rear vent duct adapter because of issues with my own house so be prepared for that. The hood also came setup for direct wiring so I had to install a chord. There is a nice little junction box already there to do this but you'll need to buy the chord, screw on connector things, and a wire clamp. Total installation time including changing out top vent for the included rear vent parts, rewiring, and mounting screw installation was about 2 hours. Messing around with my ductwork added another hour but that's not the fault of the hood.

Lastly check for any whistling before putting the bottom cover back on. Due to the duct modifications I had made there was an annoying high pitched whistle that was fixed with a piece of aluminum tape.

title: Simple replacement, inexpensive, metal
text:
DON'T REMOVE THE RIVETS!!
I have a Kenmore Elite hood and wasn't sure if these would work, but since the photos of the hood appeared very similar to mine, I figured I'd try them since both sides of the center one was broken 11 years ago when I moved in, and now another side broke. I'm not a duct tape person and my screens need to be in place.

My old brackets are plastic (these are spring metal with a hole in the center!) so I carefully bent and broke off the remaining bracket and a half. I left the 3 rivets intact, cleaned the areas with alcohol where the new ones would adhere, dried them and cleaned and dried them again. I took a pair of scissors and poked a hole in the adhesive where the hole is on each, peeled off the protective paper, pressed the brackets over the rivets, and inserted the screens! Done deal!

Oh, the frames have 2 notches cut out that, if you feel the front of the hood where those match to, would be to hold the screens in place. After many years, those notches were bent inward. I took something metel and, placing it gently inside the holes, bent the frame back to flatten them out.

Just like new, no more falling out when I close a cabinet! Being metal, I'm sure I'll never have to replace them EVER!

text: I use gallons of ice each day.  I need an ice maker.  The previous one lasted for two years.  This looked like the same model.  (Frankly, all the stand-alone ice makers look alike.)  One immediately obvious difference: the previous model used a light-beam to detect a full tray; this one uses a thermometer.  Not a huge deal: it notices a full tray a little later with the thermometer.  Then I heard the click-click-click.  The ice scooper was jammed.  I un-jammed it.  Fine.  Now it jams every hour.  When it jams, it turns on the full and out-of-water lights when it is neither full nor low on water.  I don't have to un-jam it, just reset it.  I have a few days to return it.  But I need an ice maker.  (As an aside, the light beam on my previous ice maker should have been modulated on the send-side and filtered on the receive-side so that direct sunlight wouldn't have let it overfill.  Duct tape over the window solved that problem.)
